PCoA analysis by rural_urban_status

AI-generated Summary

The PERMANOVA test results indicate a significant difference (P-value = 0.002) between the samples, with an explained variance (R2) of 12.4%. The Multidimensional Scaling (MDS) analysis shows that the separation of samples is most pronounced on MDS1 axis, where FDR (False Discovery Rate) is below 0.1 (FDR = 0.00860972722461336), making it statistically significant. The urban group appears to be enriched along this axis, suggesting that the rural-urban status might play a key role in the observed variation among samples. However, no other MDS axes were found to be significantly separated based on the FDR threshold of 0.1. This suggests that the urban versus rural distinction might be the main driver of differences between the samples, while other factors may have less impact on the observed patterns.

Alpha-diversity analysis by rural_urban_status

AI-generated Summary

The results suggest that there is a statistically significant difference in alpha diversity at both the genus and species level between the rural and urban groups. Specifically, the rural group exhibits higher richness (number of taxa) and Shannon diversity (a measure of evenness and abundance) for both genera and species compared to the urban group. However, it's important to note that these results are significant at a 5% level (P-value < 0.05). The rest of the alpha diversity indexes were not found to be significantly different between the two groups. This suggests that the difference in diversity may be primarily driven by the rural-urban status, with rural environments having a higher abundance and evenness of species compared to urban environments.

The genus level includes Bacteroides, Prevotella, Faecalibacterium, Roseburia, Escherichia-Shigella, Agathobacter, Blautia, Subdoligranulum, Phascolarctobacterium, and Parasutterella. The abundance of the phyla varies between the rural and urban groups, with Firmicutes being more abundant in the rural group (48.97%) compared to the urban group (43.85%). Proteobacteria is more abundant in the urban group (7.92%) compared to the rural group (3.26%), while Fusobacteriota and Desulfobacterota are more abundant in the rural group (0.09% and 0.29%, respectively) compared to the urban group (1.32% and 0.19%, respectively). Cyanobacteria is more abundant in the rural group (0.12%) compared to the urban group (0.01%), while Euryarchaeota and Synergistota are present only in the rural group (0.01% and 0.001%, respectively). At the genus level, Bacteroides and Prevotella are more abundant in the urban group (36.88% and 5.54%, respectively) compared to the rural group (19.63% and 19.39%, respectively), while Faecalibacterium, Roseburia, Agathobacter, Blautia, Subdoligranulum, Phascolarctobacterium, and Parasutterella have a higher abundance in the rural group (9.99%, 3.49%, 2.14%, 2.40%, 1.17%, 1.44%, and 0.57%, respectively) compared to the urban group (6.77%, 3.55%, 2.59%, 1.89%, 2.33%, 1.77%, and 2.17%, respectively). A significant portion of the samples also contain "Other" taxa, which make up 40.26% in the rural group and 31.53% in the urban group.

2. In the urban group, there is an enrichment of taxa within the phylum Bacteroidota, including Bacteroidaceae, specifically Bacteroides, Burkholderiales (Sutterellaceae with Sutterella), and Fusobacteriota (Fusobacteriaceae with Fusobacterium).

All these taxa have a False Discovery Rate (FDR) less than 0.05, indicating they are significant and likely not due to random chance. These findings suggest that differences in bacterial composition may exist between rural and urban groups, with rural environments potentially being more dominated by Actinobacteriota and Clostridia, while urban environments might be more influenced by Bacteroidota, Burkholderiales, Fusobacteriota, and Firmicutes (excluding Coriobacteriia).

AI-generated Discussion

Title: Differences in Microbial Composition between Rural and Urban Environments: An Analysis of Gut Microbiome

In the present study, we aimed to investigate the potential differences in microbial composition between rural and urban environments, focusing on the gut microbiome. The results from the PERMANOVA test revealed a significant difference (P-value = 0.002) between the samples with an explained variance (R2) of 12.4%. Multidimensional Scaling (MDS) analysis showed that the separation of samples was most pronounced on MDS1 axis, where FDR was below 0.1 (FDR = 0.00860972722461336), suggesting that the rural-urban status might play a key role in the observed variation among samples.

At the phylum level, Firmicutes and Bacteroidota were the most abundant, with Firmicutes being more abundant in the rural group (48.97%) compared to the urban group (43.85%). Proteobacteria was more abundant in the urban group (7.92%) compared to the rural group (3.26%), while Cyanobacteria was more abundant in the rural group (0.12%) compared to the urban group (0.01%). The abundance of several phyla varied between the two groups, indicating potential differences in bacterial composition.

At the genus level, Bacteroides and Prevotella were more abundant in the urban group (36.88% and 5.54%, respectively) compared to the rural group (19.63% and 19.39%, respectively), while Faecalibacterium, Roseburia, Agathobacter, Blautia, Subdoligranulum, Phascolarctobacterium, and Parasutterella had a higher abundance in the rural group (9.99%, 3.49%, 2.14%, 2.40%, 1.17%, 1.44%, and 0.57%, respectively) compared to the urban group (6.77%, 3.55%, 2.59%, 1.89%, 2.33%, 1.77%, and 2.17%, respectively).

The statistical analysis indicated significant differences in bacterial composition between rural and urban groups for several taxa within the phylum Bacteria, including an enrichment of the family Coriobacteriaceae (specifically Collinsella), order Coriobacteriales, class Coriobacteriia, phylum Actinobacteriota, unspecified taxa within Clostridia (Lachnospiraceae_FCS020_group) and Oscillospirales (unclassified) in the rural group. In contrast, taxa within the phylum Bacteroidota, including Bacteroidaceae, specifically Bacteroides, Burkholderiales (Sutterellaceae with Sutterella), and Fusobacteriota (Fusobacteriaceae with Fusobacterium) were more abundant in the urban group.

The results suggest that differences in diversity may be primarily driven by rural-urban status, with rural environments having a higher abundance and evenness of species compared to urban environments, as indicated by significant differences in alpha diversity at both the genus and species level. These findings indicate the presence of potential differences in microbial composition between rural and urban environments that might be influenced by various factors such as diet, lifestyle, and exposure to pollution. Further investigations are warranted to better understand the mechanisms underlying these differences and their implications for human health and disease.
